  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Bovine Herpes Virus-4 as a Vaccine Vector for Theileria parva, the Cause of East Coast Fever</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Support the science and practice of food, feed, and fiber production (including forestry, wildlife, fisheries, aquaculture and floriculture) and its relationships to natural resources, processing, marketing, distribution, utilization (including nutrition), and trade.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This award strives to support the science and practice of food, feed, and fiber production (including forestry, wildlife, fisheries, aquaculture and floriculture) and its relationships to natural resources, processing, marketing, distribution, utilization (including nutrition), and trade. In addition, this award Test the hypothesis that delivery of T. parva schizont antigens via a Bovine Herpes Virus-4 (BHV-4) platform induces parasite-specific immune responses in cattle that prevent morbidity and mortality. Specific objectives proposed to test this hypothesis are: (1) determine the functional activity and duration of immune responses to T. parva induced by recombinant BHV-4 immunization; and (2) test the ability of immunized cattle to resist T. parva challenge..</narrative>
  </description>
